14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>In English, the disease
is called:</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:normal'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Inflammatory disease of liver</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:18.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Causes</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Viruses&nbsp;</span></b><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>- currently there are 5 main types of virus that can cause
hepatitis: A, B, C, D, E.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Viruses
A&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>(HAV) and&nbsp;<b>E&nbsp;</b>(HEV) cause enteral (food and
waterborne) hepatitis.&nbsp;The transmission mechanism is fecal-oral.&nbsp;The
source is a sick person.&nbsp;Hepatitis A and E do not have a chronic course
and occur only in an acute form.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Hepatitis
B&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>(HBV),&nbsp;<b>C&nbsp;</b>(HCV) and&nbsp;<b>D&nbsp;</b>(HDV)&nbsp;<b>viruses&nbsp;</b>are
sources of parenteral (blood-borne) hepatitis.&nbsp;Infection occurs through
contact of damaged skin or mucous membranes with blood or other biological
fluids of the carrier.&nbsp;The main routes of transmission: sexual, vertical
(from mother to child), household (razors, scissors, etc.), parenteral (through
needles and other medical instruments).&nbsp;Hepatitis B, C, D can occur in
both acute and chronic form.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>In recent years,
hepatitis&nbsp;<b>F&nbsp;</b>,&nbsp;<b>G&nbsp;</b>,&nbsp;<b>SEN&nbsp;</b>,&nbsp;<b>TTV&nbsp;</b>viruses
have also been found&nbsp;.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Some other viruses can
also infect the liver: Epstein-Barr virus, cytomegalovirus (CMV), herpesvirus
family, Coxsackie virus, and others.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Toxic
damage&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:
"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>- it is caused by heavy metals,
pesticides, fluorinated hydrocarbons and other substances, they damage liver
tissue.&nbsp;Alcoholic and medicinal liver damage is especially
distinguished.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Medicinal hepatitis can
develop from taking almost any drug.&nbsp;The main reasons: incorrect dosage of
the drug, long-term treatment, failure to take into account the individual
characteristics of the patient when prescribing drug therapy.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>The development of
alcoholic hepatitis is associated with the effect of ethanol on the membranes
of liver cells and mitochondria, which then leads to fatty degeneration of the
liver.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Autoimmune
damage&nbsp;</span></b><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:
"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>- at the moment there is no proven cause
of the development of autoimmune hepatitis.&nbsp;It is assumed that the disease
manifests itself as a result of a combination of adverse environmental factors,
genetic predisposition and impaired immune response of the body.&nbsp;As a
result, antigens are produced against the liver's own cells with the
development of fibrosis and necrosis.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Bacteria&nbsp;</span></b><span
lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>most often attack the liver in the presence of other infectious
diseases.&nbsp;Hepatitis is especially common in tuberculosis, syphilis,
leptospirosis, typhoid and paratyphoid infections.&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Who is
